04407nam a22005175i 9780889207868DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19861986xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892078687 a10.51644/97808892078682doi  a(DE-B1597)667899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1033.H93bH39 1986eb 7aBIO0080002bisacsh04a971.061/2/09241 aHaycock, Ronald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSam Hughes :bThe Public Career of a Controversial Canadian, 1885-1916 /cRonald Haycock. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[1986] 4c©1986  a1 online resource (382 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Background, 1853-1885 -- tJournalism, the Militia, and Local Politics, 1885-1890 -- tGetting Elected, 1890-1892 -- tIn Parliament, 1892-1899 -- tHughes, Mutton, and the Contingents for South Africa, 1899 -- tThe Proving Ground: South Africa, 1900 -- tA Loyal Veteran, 1900-1911 -- tA Loyal Maverick -- tThe Peacetime Minister, 1911-1914 -- tThe Critics -- tWar and Mobilization: One Man's Show, 1914 -- tRecruiting, 1914-1916 -- t"Done in Our Own Country": War Supplies, 1914-1916 -- tHughes' Hydra Overseas, 1914-1915 -- tA Nightmare Removed: Reform and Resignation, 1916 -- tEclipse -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is based on the public career of a highly controversial Canadian, Sam Hughes 1885–1916. He is one of the most colourful, even bizarre, figures in Canadian history. Though he died in 1921, his name can still conjure up controversy and not a little misunderstanding. His long career—in so many respects the quintessential story of a poor backwoods Ontario farm boy who made good by his own efforts—continues to exert a fascination that few other Canadian political figures could duplicate. Even though there has never been a major scholarly study of Sam Hughes, historians and other writers have developed definite opinions about him, and they are held nearly as vigorously as those of his contemporaries. These vary from insisting that Hughes was mentally unbalanced to proclaiming him a genius. Hughes’ defenders have rarely been professional historians. Neither side have not produced an extensive or definitive literature on Hughes in proportion to other figures of a similar public stature. Whatever side the studies have taken, the assessments are still incomplete because they have not examined the entirety of Sam Hughes’ public life. To a large extent these limitations have allowed the folk image of him to persist. But Hughes had fibre and substance beyond this. Since historical figures must be explained in terms of their environment, this study tries to redress the previous imbalances by examining Hughes’ public career. It is the only way his historical significance can be explained and reasonable judgments made.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Military.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920786840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207868423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207868/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles